[6.6](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/business-designer-6-6)

[6.7](https://docs.doxee.com/docs/en/business-designer-6-7)

There are 2 types of permission systems in Business Designer. **Role permissions **(Role Security) and **Content permissions **(Content Security). Content permissions override role permissions, yet the user only has permission according to their role. Deleting, copying or moving for permitted elements with locked child elements is not possible.

As an example of use, the user *business_user *should be revoked from the permission for a certain element. First, select the desired element (for example, a container that contains a table) and under the advanced settings you can search for **editable-template**. Enter the command: *deny:user:business_user *to revoke the userâ€™s permission.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

This element is now grayed out for the user business_user. Changes to this element (and child elements) are no longer possible with this user:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

There are three ways to assign permissions:

- **grant**: Listed users are allowed to edit the element. Syntax: **grant:user:username**. If you want to add multiple users use: **grant:user:username1,user:username2â€¦**

- **deny**: Listed users are not allowed to edit the element. Deny applies before grant, so a user that appears on both lists is not allowed to edit. Use **deny:user:username **for a single user or **deny:user:username1,user:username2â€¦ **for multiple users.

- **only**: Listed users are allowed to edit the element, all other users have no writing permissions, which breaks the inheritance of higher elements. Use **only:user:username **or **only:user:username1,user:username2â€¦**

You can set grant, deny or only for users (see above), groups (use: **grant:group:groupname**) or roles (use: **grant:role:rolename**)

## Role permissions
- permission to elements in the entire Web Designer application

- no inheritance of rights in the element hierarchy

- predefined standard roles: READER, BUSINESS_USER, POWER_USER and ADMIN

- individual roles are configurable

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## Content permissions
- permissions on special elements within a template or module

- inheritance of permissions in the element hierarchy

- explicit permission on inherited prohibitions possible
